As you are probably aware, the ████ voted 5-0 to reject instituting retail 
rate caps in █████████ and instead adopted SDG&E's proposal to refund over 
$100 million.  The ██████████ also approved ███ and ████'s motion to enter 
into bilateral agreements and schedule those transactions through the ██ 
using the bilateral-option market.  These transactions will be confidential 
and will be disclosed only to the ██████████'s energy division, for purposes 
of reasonableness.  The ██████████ did not act upon █████████'s advice letter 
(#1242) to facilitate customer awareness of competitive alternatives.  That 
advice letter will not be acted upon until ███████████████████ meeting in 
█████████.

The ██████████ has also opened an investigation into the role of the utility 
as a default provider and will explore how the utility should pass along its 
costs to the customers.  It will also address whether SDG&E should be 
authorized to participate in bilateral contracts in addition to ██ 
purchases.  It also opens the door to consider alternative exchange.  This is 
a fast track investigation, so I will set up a call to discuss ████████████████.

███di McCubbin and I were in ██████████ █████████ meeting with several of the 
key legislative offices.  There was also an interested party meeting (█████████████████████████████).  From those meetings, it was apparent that ███████████ 
is interested in legislation to institute rate caps in █████████, re-vamp the 
governance structure of the ███ and ██ boards, having market participants 
(generators, marketers, utilities) share in some of the pain that █████████'s 
consumers feel, extend the rate freeze, etc.  Although, most of the other 
legislative offices saw this proposal as a total morass.

The legislative offices that we met with, while interested in providing some 
political cover to ████ ██████ (Senator from █████████ in a close political 
race), were not interested in pursuing sweeping changes to the current 
structure, although this could change.  However, it should be noted that ████ 
██████ said ███████ that ███ would introduce rate cap legislation in ███ 
█████ when the legislature reconvenes on ████████.  Most of the discussion 
with the other offices was on what can be done by ███████████ and focused on 
bringing on peaking plants and expanding demand responsive programs.

███di and ████████████ also met with ████████████, of the Governor's Office.  
██ stated that the Governor did not want any major changes to the current 
structure to come across ███ desk, but that the Governor needed our help in 
preventing such changes from getting there, otherwise ██ may be politically 
compelled to sign the legislation.  ███di will send out more information 
later, ███'s having computer problems.

There will be a hearing █████████ of the ██████ and ███████████████ 
Committees on █████████ issues on █████████.

We, in ██, will keep you updated on developments. 